# User Type & Journey Matrix (Stage 1 Contract)

## Purpose

Define all user types, their permissions, and their core journeys across
the platform. This ensures: - consistent UI behaviour - correct access
control assumptions - clean API design later - no frontend-invented
logic

------------------------------------------------------------------------

# 1. User Types Overview

## Public User

-   Not authenticated
-   Access: Front-facing website only
-   Goals:
    -   understand platform
    -   explore applications
    -   review membership
    -   convert to signup

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Client Users

### Account Owner

-   Full control of organisation
-   Can:
    -   manage billing
    -   manage users
    -   access all entitled modules

### Billing Contact

-   Focus: payments and invoices
-   Can:
    -   view/pay invoices
    -   manage payment methods

### Team Admin

-   Manages users and access
-   Can:
    -   invite/remove users
    -   assign roles

### Standard User

-   Limited access
-   Can:
    -   use assigned modules
    -   view resources

### Read-Only User

-   View only
-   No actions

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Admin Users

### Platform Administrator

-   Full system access

### Operations Admin

-   Manages workflows and operations

### Support Admin

-   Handles tickets and issues

### Finance Admin

-   Handles billing and payments

### Content Admin

-   Manages public content

### Compliance Admin

-   Handles onboarding/compliance

------------------------------------------------------------------------

# 2. Journey Matrix

## Public Journeys

### Explore Platform

-   Start: Home
-   End: Applications/Membership
-   Actions:
    -   browse content
    -   click CTA

### Register

-   Start: Register page
-   End: Account created
-   States:
    -   success
    -   validation error

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Client Journeys

### Login → Dashboard

-   Start: Sign in
-   End: Portal dashboard
-   States:
    -   success
    -   failed login

### View Membership

-   Start: Dashboard
-   End: Membership page
-   Actions:
    -   upgrade/downgrade

### Billing Flow

-   Start: Billing page
-   Actions:
    -   pay invoice
    -   update payment
-   States:
    -   success
    -   failed payment
    -   billing hold

### Application Launch

-   Start: Applications
-   Actions:
    -   launch module
-   States:
    -   allowed
    -   restricted
    -   onboarding required

### Support Request

-   Start: Support page
-   Actions:
    -   submit ticket
-   States:
    -   submitted
    -   in progress
    -   resolved

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Admin Journeys

### Manage Customers

-   Start: Admin → Customers
-   Actions:
    -   view/edit accounts

### Manage Entitlements

-   Start: Admin → Memberships
-   Actions:
    -   assign/remove access

### Manage Applications

-   Start: Admin → Applications
-   Actions:
    -   configure visibility
    -   set launch rules

### Billing Oversight

-   Start: Admin → Billing
-   Actions:
    -   review payments
    -   trigger refunds

### Support Management

-   Start: Admin → Support
-   Actions:
    -   respond to tickets

------------------------------------------------------------------------

# 3. Cross-Surface Journeys

### Purchase → Access

-   Public → Portal → App
-   Flow:
    -   select plan
    -   pay
    -   entitlement granted
    -   module visible

### Onboarding → Activation

-   Portal
-   Flow:
    -   onboarding tasks
    -   compliance check
    -   activation

### Refund → Access Revocation

-   Admin → Portal
-   Flow:
    -   refund issued
    -   access removed or modified

------------------------------------------------------------------------

# 4. State Mapping

Each journey must support:

-   loading
-   success
-   error
-   restricted
-   pending
-   onboarding
-   billing hold

------------------------------------------------------------------------

# 5. Key Rules

1.  UI must NOT decide access
2.  Backend determines:
    -   entitlements
    -   billing status
    -   onboarding state
3.  UI only reflects state

------------------------------------------------------------------------

# 6. Output Requirements

Firebase Studio must: - reflect user types visually - support role-based
navigation - support all journey states - avoid hardcoding logic

------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Definition of Done

-   All user types defined
-   All journeys mapped
-   States covered
-   No ambiguity in access behaviour
